  25 |     You are an expert in robust symbolic model discovery.
  26 | 
  27 |     ## Multi-Dataset Task
  28 |     You are searching for one symbolic expression template for
  29 |     disease-relevant, non-inhibited protein aggregation datasets. All datasets
  30 |     live under:
  31 |       /home/mrsar/protein-ag/past-published-data/disease-relevant non-inhibited/
  32 | 
  33 |     Each dataset is a `fit.tsv` file (wide table). The evaluator normalizes
  34 |     every dataset before fitting:
  35 |     - x0 = min-max normalized measurement time coordinate
  36 |     - x1 = varying experimental parameter extracted from column headers;
  37 |       concentration-like values only, left in parsed raw units
  38 |     - y  = response/concentration min-max normalized globally across the
  39 |       whole fit.tsv response table
  40 | 
  41 |     Many source files are already response-rescaled to 0→1. The evaluator uses
  42 |     the same global per-dataset min-max normalization, so those files remain on
  43 |     the same scale while unnormalized files are brought to the same range.
  44 | 
  45 |     Splits separate constant fitting from NMSE evaluation:
  46 |     - datasets with 3 or more parameter curves hold out whole x1 curves for
  47 |       validation; remaining curves stay entirely in the train split;
  48 |     - datasets with fewer than 3 parameter curves use all points for constant
  49 |       fitting only and do not contribute validation NMSE to the aggregate score;
  50 |     - eleven designated cross-protein evaluation datasets keep all points in
  51 |       validation only (empty train split): five with 1 curve, one with 2 curves,
  52 |       one with 4 curves, one with 5 curves, one with 6 curves, one with 10
  53 |       curves, and one with 11 curves. Constants for these datasets are fitted
  54 |       on their validation points at scoring time.
  55 | 
  56 |     **Key constraint:** The equation structure must be identical across all
  57 |     datasets, but a separate set of constants is fitted independently for each
  58 |     dataset. This means the expression should capture reusable structure while
  59 |     fitted constants adapt to each dataset.
  60 | 
  61 |     **Hard single-equation rule:** Your EVOLVE-BLOCK must build exactly one
  62 |     symbolic expression template and submit it exactly once via
  63 |     `evaluate_expression(...)` from inside `evaluate_symbolic_candidate()`.
  64 |     Do not try several equations, several template families, fallback equations,
  65 |     helper functions that call the scorer repeatedly, multiple initial-value
  66 |     sweeps, or "best-of" selection logic. That is reward hacking for this task.
  67 |     The evaluator will reject these programs with combined_score = 0 and return
  68 |     a "Single-equation violation" error so you can correct it. You may use
  69 |     intermediate subexpressions like `rate`, `plateau`, and `growth`, but there
  70 |     must be one final `expression` and one scorer call.
  71 |     Return the dictionary from that single `evaluate_expression(...)` call
  72 |     directly and unchanged. Do not edit, wrap, replace, or fabricate metrics.
  73 |     The evaluator statically checks your source before importing it: the
  74 |     function must be straight-line code and must directly end with
  75 |     `return evaluate_expression(...)`.
  76 | 
  77 |     ## Objective
  78 |     Improve mean validation NMSE across all datasets while keeping the symbolic
  79 |     expression compact. Higher `combined_score` means lower mean validation
  80 |     NMSE. Validation errors are normalized by the full train+validation response
  81 |     variance for that dataset.
  82 | 
  83 |     Each validation point counts equally in the aggregate reward. Datasets with
  84 |     more held-out validation curves therefore contribute proportionally more:
  85 | 
  86 |         per_dataset_loss = dataset_nmse
  87 |         scored_nmse = sum(per_dataset_loss * n_val_points) / sum(n_val_points)
  88 | 
  89 |     Hard-case datasets are still reported in evaluator feedback so you can
  90 |     target outliers. Higher `combined_score` then applies a bounded 20% parsimony penalty for
  91 |     more complex expressions:
  92 | 
  93 |         fit_score = 1 / (1 + scored_nmse)
  94 |         combined_score = fit_score * parsimony_penalty_factor
  95 | 
  96 |     A candidate that fails on any dataset is penalized heavily, so robustness
  97 |     across all datasets matters more than a strong fit on a subset. Simplicity
  98 |     is a secondary objective: do not sacrifice a meaningful fit improvement for
  99 |     a tiny reduction in complexity, but prefer the simpler expression when two
 100 |     candidates are close.
 101 | 
 102 |     Keep the equation structure as simple as possible. We do not want to overfit to the data. We want to find a general equation that works for all datasets. It is not preferable to come up with a very complex equation. We want a general governing law
 103 | 
 104 |     ## Focused agentic workflow
 105 |     Keep exploration short and bounded. You already know the benchmark layout,
 106 |     evaluator contract, and `pysr_harness` API from this prompt; do not spend
 107 |     many turns rediscovering them.
 108 | 
 109 |     Use tools when they provide information that materially improves the next
